                                                   CRICKET BRIEFS
                      
	 Dhoni amp;amp; Co. go through fitness test
    
	New Delhi: Eight Indian cricketers, including captain Mahendra Singh Dhoni, went through a three-hour fitness test under the watchful eyes of the South African coach Gary Kirsten at the Kotla ground here on Monday. The other cricketers who were present were Harbhajan Singh, Ashish Nehra, RP Singh, Gautam Gambhir, Praveen Kumar, Suresh Raina and Ishant Sharma. Virender Sehwag, recovering from a shoulder injury, was not present.  
	The tests were for players from north, central and east zones. Yuvraj Singh will attend the session in Mumbai on Tuesday with players from west and south.         
	Later, Kirsten said that the results of the tests would be compared with the results of tests taken at the National Cricket Academy during the four-day preparatory camp from August 27.         
	WI dispute         
	 Georgetown: The contract dispute between the West Indies Cricket Board and the players has not been resolved despite the intervention of a regional statesman. The Caribbean Community, a trade bloc of 15 countries in the region, appointed former Commonwealth secretary general Shridath Ramphal to mediate but said Monday in a statement that they have finished without an overall agreement.         
	Luke in trouble         
	 Melbourne: Australian batsman Luke Pomersbach, who played for the Kings XI Punjab in the Indian Premier League, will have to appear in court on Friday for allegedly assaulting policemen while trying to evade custody after a car accident. Poilce said Pomerbasch was drunk at the time of the incident.         
	BCCI meeting         
	 Mumbai: The Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI)s working committee, which meets here on Thursday, would decide whether former Indian Cricket League players can take part in the Indian Premier League to be held in March-April next year.         
	Mortaza surgery         
	 Dhaka: Injured Bangladesh captain Mashrafe Mortaza will be out of action for six weeks after undergoing surgery on Monday, officials said.         
	PCB audit         
	 Karachi: Pakistans auditor generals office has refused to submit a report on the Pakistan Cricket Board to the standing committee of sports, constituted by National Assembly (NA). Sources in the sports ministry said that the auditor generals office has said that it is only authorised to submit the report to the NAs public accounts committee.         
	Younis claim         
	 Karachi: Pakistan captain Younis Khan said that he is confident that his side will either win the upcoming Champions Trophy in September or the 2011 World Cup. The pool of players includes some talented players and if things go well, I am sure we can win one of the two big tournaments coming up, he said.           SPORTSDESK AMP; AGENCIES                                                                                                                   
